Hello @wang-xinyu, thank you for your interest in our work! Please visit our [Custom Training Tutorial](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov3/wiki/Train-Custom-Data) to get started, and see our [Google Colab Notebook](https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1G8T-VFxQkjDe4idzN8F-hbIBqkkkQnxw), [Docker Image](https://hub.docker.com/r/ultralytics/yolov3), and [GCP Quickstart Guide](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov3/wiki/GCP-Quickstart) for example environments. 
  
If this is a bug report, please provide screenshots and **minimum viable code to reproduce your issue**, otherwise we can not help you.
@wang-xinyu hmm great, that's a good FPS! What are the main use cases for tensorrt? I'm not very familiar with it.

@glenn-jocher 

> NVIDIA TensorRTâ„¢ is an SDK for high-performance deep learning inference. It includes a deep learning inference optimizer and runtime that delivers low latency and high-throughput for deep learning inference applications.

It's used for model deployment on NVIDIA GPU, like 2080, titan, T4, jetson TX2, etc.
It can make model run faster, and save GPU memory.

This page is an official intro for TensorRT.
[https://developer.nvidia.com/tensorrt](https://developer.nvidia.com/tensorrt)

@wang-xinyu ahhh got it. That's really interesting, then yes it could be very useful. I can add a link to your repo on the readme. 

How would one convert a trained model on a custom dataset to tensorrt format?

@glenn-jocher thanks, that would be great!

For how to convert yolov3-spp weights, I described in this readme [tensorrtx/yolov3-spp](https://github.com/wang-xinyu/tensorrtx/tree/master/yolov3-spp).

Shortly, we wrote a `gen_wts.py`, which can convert your `*.pt` to `*.wts`, and then load `*.wts` in tensorrt.

For the `wts format`, I described in a tutorial [the-wts-content-format](https://github.com/wang-xinyu/tensorrtx/tree/master/getting_started#the-wts-content-format), which is quite easy to understand.

For all `yolov3-spp.cfg` traind weights, one can just use `gen_wts.py` to convert weights.

For other `cfgs`, like `yolov3-spp-1cls.cfg`, one have to adapt the cpp codes, only minor changes are needed.
@wang-xinyu got it, sounds good! Maybe we can link to your github in the tutorials section of the readme? Could you submit a PR for that?
